A '''metroplex''' is a contiguous metropolitan area that has more than one principal anchor city of near equal size or importance, commonly associated with the [[Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}} According to the North Texas Commission (NTC), the term is a [[portmanteau]] of the terms "metropolitan" and "complex"{{Failed verification|date=October 2018}} and was created by an advertising agency.{{Which|date=October 2018}} The NTC [[trademark]]ed the term "Dallas/Fort Worth Metroplex" in 1972 as a replacement for the previously-ubiquitous "North Texas".<ref name="NTCHistory">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntc-dfw.org/ntchistory.html|author=North Texas Commission|title=History|year=2013|accessdate=1 October 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215253/http://www.ntc-dfw.org/ntchistory.html|archivedate=4 October 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Urban areas with smaller secondary anchor cities (such as [[Mexico City]], [[New York City]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Houston]], [[Chicago]], and [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]) are not considered metroplexes.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}

